<entry>
<author><name><![CDATA[Gaurav]]></name></author>
<updated>2013-02-07T07:43:25-07:00</updated>
<published>2013-02-07T07:43:25-07:00</published>
<id>http://www.classicshell.net/forum/viewtopic.php?t=211&amp;p=920#p920</id>
<link href="http://www.classicshell.net/forum/viewtopic.php?t=211&amp;p=920#p920"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: Copy UI - Windows 8]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://www.classicshell.net/forum/viewtopic.php?t=211&amp;p=920#p920"><![CDATA[
You *can* keep both by checking the topmost boxes but yes it's too many clicks and the buttons aren't even close to each other. Windows 8 did add skipping files based on the same date and size but it's not checked by default, nor does it save its last state. Calculating checksums for each and every file in the copy list would be too time and CPU-intensive.<br /><br />You can still have the good old XP style &quot;classic&quot; UI if you use <strong>PerigeeCopy</strong>, another free open source tool and it's speed is pretty much the same as the Windows built-in copy in my benchmarks: <!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://jstanley.pingerthinger.com/pscopy.html">http://jstanley.pingerthinger.com/pscopy.html</a><!-- m --> . It also has the ability to queue copy jobs, so only one operates at a time, copy only newer files, skip all errors till the end, postpone overwrite questions till the end, or absolutely not prompt at all no matter what. It also uses native Windows UI, since I cannot stand ugly custom interfaces.<br /><br />It's a perfect fit for incorporating into Classic Shell and further improving. <img src="http://www.classicshell.net/forum/images/smilies/icon_mrgreen.gif" alt=":mrgreen:" title="Mr. Green" /><br /><br />Here's an article on PerigeeCopy: <!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://winaero.com/blog/queue-copy-and-move-operations-in-windows-with-perigeecopy/">http://winaero.com/blog/queue-copy-and- ... rigeecopy/</a><!-- m --> and a screenshot.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://www.classicshell.net/forum/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=54">Gaurav</a> — Thu Feb 07, 2013 7:43 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
</entry>
